{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2024-08-29T17:40:40.256541+00:00", "modified": "2024-08-29T17:40:40.883967+00:00", "id": 13517854, "conceptrecid": "13517853", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13517854", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.13517853", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.13517854", "metadata": {"title": "Characteristics and Risk Perceptions of Ghanaians Potentially Exposed to Bat-Borne Zoonoses through Bushmeat", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13517854", "publication_date": "2015", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Emerging zoonotic pathogens from wildlife pose increasing public health threats globally. Bats, in particular, host an array of zoonotic pathogens, yet there is little research on how bats and humans interact, how people perceive bats and their accompanying disease risk, or who is most at risk. Eidolon helvum, the largest and most abundant African fruit bat species, is widely hunted and eaten in Ghana and also carries potentially zoonotic pathogens. This combination raises concerns, as hunting and butchering bushmeat are common sources of zoonotic transmission. Through a combination of interviews with 577 Ghanaians across southern Ghana, we identified the characteristics of people involved in the bat-bushmeat trade and we explored their perceptions of risk. Bat hunting, selling and consumption are widely distributed across regional and ethnic lines, with hotspots in certain localities, while butchering is predominantly done by women and active hunters. Interviewees held little belief of disease risk from bats, saw no ecological value in fruit bats and associated the consumption of bats with specific tribes. These data can be used to inform disease and conservation management plans, drawing on social contexts and ensuring that local voices are heard within the larger global effort to study and mitigate outbreaks.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Kamins, Alexandra O.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Rowcl